TY  - JOUR
AU  - Shapiro, Joel
AU  - Skeie, David
T1  - Information Management in Banking Crises
PY  - 2015
Y1  - 2015/08/01
DO  - 10.1093/rfs/hhv010
JO  - The Review of Financial Studies
JA  - Rev Financ Stud
VL  - 28
IS  - 8
SP  - 2322
EP  - 2363
SN  - 0893-9454
AB  - A regulator resolving a bank faces two audiences: depositors, who may run if they believe the regulator will not provide capital, and banks, which may take excess risk if they believe the regulator will provide capital. When the regulator's cost of injecting capital is private information, it manages expectations by using costly signals: (1) a regulator with a low cost of injecting capital may forbear on bad banks to signal toughness and reduce risk taking, and (2) a regulator with a high cost of injecting capital may bail out bad banks to increase confidence and prevent runs.
Y2  - 3/26/2024
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1093/rfs/hhv010
ER  - 



