TY  - JOUR
AU  - Kumar, Alok
AU  - Niessen-Ruenzi, Alexandra
AU  - Spalt, Oliver G.
T1  - What's in a Name? Mutual Fund Flows When Managers Have Foreign-Sounding Names
PY  - 2015
Y1  - 2015/08/01
DO  - 10.1093/rfs/hhv017
JO  - The Review of Financial Studies
JA  - Rev Financ Stud
VL  - 28
IS  - 8
SP  - 2281
EP  - 2321
SN  - 0893-9454
AB  - We show that name-induced stereotypes affect the investment choices of U.S. mutual fund investors. Managers with foreign-sounding names have about 10% lower annual fund flows, and this effect is stronger among funds with investor clienteles more likely to be suspicious of foreigners. Foreign-named managers experience lower appreciation (greater decline) in flows following good (bad) performance. Following 9/11, flows to funds with managers with Middle-Eastern-sounding names declined abnormally. In an experimental setting in which skill differences are absent, individuals allocate 11% less money to an index fund managed by a foreign-named manager. This gap widens following the Boston marathon bombings.
Y2  - 3/26/2024
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1093/rfs/hhv017
ER  - 



